# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1962-new-york-mets-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The **1899 Cleveland Spiders season** was the team's 13th and final season in Major League Baseball (MLB), and their 11th season in the National League (NL).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders' team owners, the Robison family, also owned the St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] To strengthen the Perfectos, they transferred the Spiders' best players to St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis before the season, leaving Cleveland with a severely depleted roster.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] As the Spiders played abysmally and continued to lose that season, fans stopped attending their home games, and other teams refused to travel to Cleveland to play road games against the Spiders.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] This resulted in the Spiders being forced to play most of their games on the road.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL, with a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] This remains the worst single-season record for an MLB team in terms of both losses and of winning percentage (.130).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The team allowed 1,252 runs while only scoring 529, a run differential of −723 for the season, the worst in MLB history.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Spiders pitchers hit 109 batters, setting an MLB single-season record that would stand for 123 years until the 2022 Cincinnati Reds hit 110 batters.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] In early 1899, the owners of the Spiders, brothers Frank and Stanley Robison, bought the St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis Browns baseball club from Chris von der Ahe, renaming it the Perfectos.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] However, they continued to retain ownership of the Cleveland club, an obvious conflict of interest that was later prohibited by MLB.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Robisons decided that a good team in St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis would draw more fans, so they transferred most of the Cleveland stars, including future Hall of Famers Cy Young, Jesse Burkett, and Bobby Wallace, as well as manager Patsy Tebeau to St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Most of the players Cleveland received were non-entities.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Jack Clements (known to history as one of MLB's few left-handed throwing catchers) and Joe Quinn were at the end of successful careers, and player-manager Lave Cross was traded back to St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis after the Spiders got off to an 8–30 start.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] They also transferred numerous home games to the road—including the original Opening Day game to St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] As a result, the Spiders did not play their first home game until May 1.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] In early April, the Spiders started training in Terre Haute, Indiana.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Because of the cold weather, the team had to practice inside a gymnasium.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] With a decimated roster, it was apparent almost from the start that the Spiders would make a wretched showing.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] After a poor start on the road, the Spiders played a home-opening doubleheader on May 1 in front of 100 fans.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] They split the two games, moving up to 11th place.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] However, they were back in last before long.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] On June 2, the Spiders led the Brooklyn Superbas, 10–0, in the sixth inning, but they blew the lead and ended up losing, 11–10.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] On June 11, the Spiders lost to the Cincinnati Reds, 10–1, behind Frank Bates' poor pitching.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] It was the Spiders' 11th straight loss on that road trip.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The following day, the Spiders returned home and lost to the Pittsburgh Pirates in front of 58 fans.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The team kept losing games, and losses came more and more frequently as the season went on.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] On August 16, with Bates pitching, the Spiders lost to the Superbas, 13–2.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] This led to criticism from the *Cleveland Plain Dealer*.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] On August 18, the first-place Superbas completed their sweep of the Spiders, outscoring them, 43–8, in four games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders notched their 100th loss of the season on August 31, falling to the Superbas, 9–3.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Two days later, the Spiders played a local amateur team in Johnstown, Pennsylvania, and lost, 7–5.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] On September 12, the Spiders lost both games of a doubleheader to the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] At that point, they were 19–114 and had broken the MLB single-season record for losses, which had been 113.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] On October 15, the Spiders ended their season by losing both games of a doubleheader to the Cincinnati Reds, by scores of 16–1 and 19–3.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders finished in 12th place, last in the NL.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] After losing 40 of their last 41 games, they had a record of 20–134 (.130).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Their record is still the worst in Major League Baseball history.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] They trailed the pennant-winning Brooklyn Superbas by 84 games, and finished 35 games behind the 11th place Washington Senators.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] For comparison, this would project to 21–141 under the current schedule, and Pythagorean expectation based on the Spiders' results and the current 162-game schedule would translate to a record of 25–137.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The team's longest winning streak of the season was two games, which they accomplished once: on May 20 against the Phillies and May 21 against the Colonels.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] They also accumulated the second-longest losing streak in league history, at 24 games from August 26 to September 16, trailing only the 26-game losing streak set by the 1889 Louisville Colonels.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were winless against two teams: Brooklyn and Cincinnati.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Spiders opponents scored ten or more runs 49 times in 154 games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Pitchers Jim Hughey (4–30) and Charlie Knepper (4–22) tied for the team lead in wins.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The pitching staff allowed a record 1,252 runs in 154 games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders batters combined to hit 12 home runs, matching former Spiders star Bobby Wallace, who hit 12 home runs for St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The 1899 Spiders did lead the league in one statistic—games played.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Cleveland was the only team in the league to finish all of its games in the then-154 game schedule of the 1899 season, a rather unusual occurrence in that era.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Due to poor attendance, the Spiders played 112 road games, as a result of 35 of their planned home games being moved.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] In early 1899, team Robison Brothers publicly announced their intention to run the Spiders "as a sideshow", and fans took them at their word: after the first 16 home games, Cleveland's total attendance was 3,179, for a trifling average of 199 people per game.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] As a result, other NL teams refused to travel to Cleveland's League Park, since their cut of the ticket revenue would not even come close to covering their travel and hotel expenses.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] As a result, the Spiders only played 26 more home games for the rest of the season, including only eight after July 1.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Their records of 112 road games and 101 road losses will never be threatened: it is currently unbreakable under MLB's current scheduling practices, where a team plays a maximum of 81 road games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The only time it was even considered approachable was the aforementioned 1994 Mariners, but the strike of that season ended the possibility of them breaking the record, and no team has played more than 81 road games since then (not counting 1 or 3 game tiebreaker playoff games).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] A mere 6,088 fans paid for Spiders home games in 1899, an average of 145 people per game.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis drew 373,909 fans for their home season, including 15,000 for one game (their home opener against the Spiders).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The dismal 1899 season was the end for the Spiders, and for National League baseball in Cleveland.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Spiders were disbanded, along with the original Baltimore Orioles, the Louisville Colonels (Louisville, nor the entire state of Kentucky, has had another professional sports team since), and the original Washington Senators, as the National League contracted from 12 teams to 8.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The departure of baseball from Cleveland left an opening for the upstart American League, which opened for business in 1901 as a second major league and included among its charter members a new team, the Cleveland Blues.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Blues still exist today as the Cleveland Guardians.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Currently, the 2024 Chicago White Sox (121) has the post-1900 AL and MLB records for most losses in a season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] After the Spiders folded, a National League team would not play in Cleveland again until the Brooklyn Robins visited the then-Cleveland Indians in the 1920 World Series.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis, the Perfectos were renamed the St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] Louis Cardinals in 1900, which they are still called today.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1899-cleveland-spiders] The Robisons purchasing of the Browns/Perfectos/Cardinals essentially began a turnaround for the organization, as they eventually became one of the most recognizable teams in baseball in the 20th century, appearing in 15 World Series and winning 9.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The **1952 Pittsburgh Pirates season** was the team's 71st season in Major League Baseball, and their 66th season in the National League.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates posted a record of 42 wins and 112 losses, their worst record since 1890, and one of the worst in major league history.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates were led in 1952 by 70-year-old general manager Branch Rickey and 60-year-old manager Billy Meyer.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Meyer had led Pittsburgh to a last-place finish in the National League in 1950.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] After Rickey was installed as general manager, the Pirates were second-to-last in 1951.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Tension was high as the two-year contract of their star slugger, Ralph Kiner, expired before the 1952 season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Kiner was the premier power hitter in baseball, having won the previous six National League home run titles.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Rickey voiced what he viewed as inconsistent levels of commitment by Kiner when talking to the media.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Kiner received permission to instead negotiate directly with owner John W.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Galbreath and agreed to a reported one-year, $90,000 contract, making him the highest-paid player in the National League.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Kiner was signed, but the most famous Pirate of all, 78-year-old Hall of Fame member Honus Wagner, decided to retire from his part-time coaching duties with the team.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] His number was retired, and he was given a lifetime pass to Forbes Field.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Rickey wanted to hold a tryout for dozens of kids from the low minor league levels, and his plan was largely supported by Bing Crosby and the rest of the team's ownership.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Rickey hired his former scout and coach Clyde Sukeforth, who had scouted Jackie Robinson for Rickey in the 1940s.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Several top young prospects, like Vern Law and Danny O'Connell, were called to military service for the Korean War, and the more experienced Danny Murtaugh retired to accept a minor league managing position.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Expectations were high for 23-year-old outfielder Gus Bell to support Kiner in the lineup.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Murry Dickson, who had won 21 games in 1951, nearly a third of the entire team's win total, was once again expected to be the anchor of the pitching rotation.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirates struggled throughout spring training in 1952.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Gus Bell missed training time due to family-related car problems and illness and was sent to the minor leagues.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Towards the end of spring training, pitcher Bill Werle was suspended indefinitely and fined $500, only the third player fined in over two decades of Billy Meyer's managing career.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Werle professed his innocence and was reinstated before Opening Day but he was traded to the St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Thirteen rookies made the Pirates' Opening Day roster, including four teenagers: Bobby Del Greco, Tony Bartirome, Jim Waugh and Lee Walls.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] After four games, Pittsburgh's record was 2–2 but they quickly tumbled to the bottom of the majors by losing 16 of their next 17 games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The early two-game winning streak matched the longest they would see all year.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Their top three pitchers combined to win just one of their first nine games started.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Kiner's hitting was affected by the lack of support as well as back problems and his batting average was under .220 several weeks into the season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Kiner's difficulties and a club-earned run average over five resulted in a 5–28 record in mid-May.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Gus Bell returned from the minors on May 12 and hit for some power but Kiner hit only .241 with 13 home runs and 31 RBIs in the first half which ended with Pittsburgh at 21–59.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] 21-year-old Dick Groat was one of the Pirates' few bright spots in the first half with four hits in his first three games, but others went into long slumps like Jack Merson's 0-for-35, Clyde McCullough's 0-for-24 and Tony Bartirome's 0-for-29.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The second half soon resembled the first with a 2–11 stretch in mid-July.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] They were mathematically eliminated from pennant contention on August 6 with more than six weeks left to play.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In early August, Pittsburgh called up 20-year-old pitcher Ron Necciai from the minors.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Necciai had pitched a legendary 27-strikeout game in the minors but gave up five runs in his first inning in the majors.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Necciai not only finished the season with poor numbers but also injured his arm and never again pitched in the majors.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Branch Rickey's youth movement, derided as "Operation Peach Fuzz", continued unabated.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On August 20, the average age of Pittsburgh's starting lineup was only 23 with Kiner and Garagiola being the only non-rookies.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On September 5, pitcher Bill Bell made his major league debut at age 18.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Including Bell, seven of the eight youngest players in the National League in 1952 were Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The "Rickey Dinks", as they were sometimes called, were not only young but small.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] In one game, the entire infield was less than six feet tall.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The Pirate's difficulties reached off the field as well.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Ralph Kiner, enduring his worst season to date, received a death threat in an attempt to extort $6,200.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Rather than pay, he contacted the authorities and was kept under guard for a time.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Financially, Pittsburgh's attendance was the lowest since World War II, falling more than 30% short of the one million budgeted.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Branch Rickey sometimes saved money by sending only 21 players on road trips.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The final losses for the franchise, including minor leagues and bonuses, were $800,000.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Billy Meyer resigned as manager on September 27, the second-to-last day of the season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] When the season mercifully ended, Pittsburgh's final record was 42–112.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The winning percentage and number of losses were the worst for the franchise since the 1890 season (which was greatly affected by the inclusion of the Players' League) and the worst for any franchise since the 1935 Boston Braves.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Since 1952, the only non-expansion team to finish worse has been the 2003 Detroit Tigers.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] A few individuals came away with positive notes.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] A late-season home run surge by Ralph Kiner brought him his seventh consecutive home run championship (he finished tied with Hank Sauer with 37 on the year).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Dick Groat finished at .284 and was third in National League Rookie of the Year voting.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Joe Garagiola logged the most playing time of his career and hit .273 with a career-high 54 RBIs, third most on the team behind only Kiner and Gus Bell.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] On the flip side, teenagers Tony Bartirome and Bobby Del Greco were regulars but neither hit over .220.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Seven other players had at least 40 at-bats but hit under .200.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Kiner's home run total (37) was more than the next four highest on the team combined (16, 8, 7, 5).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] As a team, Pittsburgh was last in the National League in runs, hits, doubles, triples, home runs, RBIs, batting average, slugging percentage, complete games, ERA, walks allowed, home runs allowed, fielding percentage and errors committed.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Murry Dickson, who won 21 games in 1951, lost 20 games in 1952, going 14–20.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Only three other pitchers won more than two games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The pitching staff walked 615 opposing batters while striking out only 564, with 16 different players starting a game during the season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Among their young players, only Jim Waugh – the youngest – played in the majors again before 1955.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Waugh played in 1953, his last year; Ron Necciai and Tony Bartirome never played in the majors after 1952; Bill Bell pitched one inning in 1955, his last; and Bobby Del Greco, Lee Walls and Ron Kline had longer careers but not until several years later.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] Dick Groat and pitcher Bob Friend were the only players to endure the 1952 season who also played with the 1960 World Series champion Pirates.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] The failure of the 1952 Pirates was the source of several anecdotes and side stories.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] *Pittsburgh Press* writer Les Biederman recalled an earlier humorous practice by giving Dick Groat a dime while he was in an 0-for-19 slump.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1952-pittsburgh-pirates-season] When Groat broke out of the slump with a 5-for-5 game, Biederman gave Kiner a quarter with similar positive results so Biederman continued giving coins to various Pirates.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The **1955 Brooklyn Dodgers season** was the 66th season for the Brooklyn Dodgers franchise in the MLB.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The Dodgers finally fulfilled the promise of many previous Dodger teams.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Although the club had won several pennants in the past, and had won as many as 105 games in 1953, it had never won a World Series.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] This team finished 13.5 games ahead in the National League pennant race, leading the league in both runs scored and fewest runs allowed.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] In the World Series, they finally beat their crosstown rivals, the New York Yankees.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] It was the Dodgers' first and only World Series championship won while located in Brooklyn.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] With their World Series victory, the '55 Dodgers became only the second wire-to-wire team (a team leading from opening day to season's end) in MLB history after the '27 Yankees.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] This season was basically a culmination of the careers of many legendary Dodger players.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Catcher Roy Campanella won the 1955 National League Most Valuable Player award, his third in five years.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Center fielder Duke Snider led the league in runs batted in and was second in the MVP voting.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] He also hit his 200th career home run on May 10.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Jackie Robinson and Pee Wee Reese, both 36 years old, could still play.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Gil Hodges, 31, hit 27 home runs (and drove in both Dodger runs in the seventh game of the Series), while Carl Furillo, 33, hit 26 home runs with a .314 batting average.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Don Newcombe, who was 20–5.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] It was the first time a black pitcher had won 20 games in a season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The 22-year-old Johnny Podres was only 9–10 but became the hero of the 1955 World Series by shutting out the Yankees in the seventh game.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Duke Snider finished second to teammate Campanella in the MVP voting by just five points, 226–221, with each man receiving eight first place votes.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The voting then as now was conducted by the Baseball Writers' Association of America.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Each voting member, one from each major league city, filled out a ballot selecting ten men.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] A player receiving a first place vote got 14 points, then values of 9–8–7–6–5–4–3–2–1 for those in places 2 through 10.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] A writer from Philadelphia who was sick and who had become hospitalized had turned in a ballot with Campanella listed in position number 1 as well as position number 5.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The assumption had been that the writer had meant to write Snider's name into one of those slots.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Unable to get a clarification from the ill writer the BBWAA, after considering disallowing the ballot, decided to accept it, count the first place vote for Campanella and count the fifth place vote as though it were left blank.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Had the ballot been disallowed, the vote would have been won by Snider by three points.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Had Snider gotten the fifth place vote, the final vote would have favored Snider 227–226.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Duke did, however, win the Sporting News National League Player of the Year Award for 1955 and the Sid Mercer Award.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The 1955 World Series proved to the only title the Dodgers won in Brooklyn.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] After losing the 1956 World Series to the Yankees, the team would move to Los Angeles after the 1957 season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] With the death of Carl Erskine in April 2024, Sandy Koufax became the last surviving player from the 1955 team.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] In August 2005, the Los Angeles Dodgers commemorated the 50th anniversary of the franchise winning its first World Series, and only one while in Brooklyn.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1955-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The eleven surviving members of the 1955 team all attended the weekend celebration.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The **1961 Major League Baseball expansion draft** was held by Major League Baseball on October 10, 1961, to fill the rosters of the New York Mets and the Houston Colt .45s.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] These new franchises were set to enter the National League (NL) as part of the 1962 Major League Baseball expansion.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Selections in the draft were limited to a pool of players designated by existing NL teams.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] Due to the poor performance of the Mets and Colt .45s after two seasons, another draft was held for the teams on October 10, 1963.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] The other existing NL clubs made four players from their 40-man roster available at $30,000 apiece.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] A maximum of eight players could be selected between the two clubs.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1961-major-league-baseball-expansion-draft] However, only three selections were made, two by New York and one by Houston.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-baltimore-orioles-season] The **1962 Baltimore Orioles season** involved the Orioles finishing seventh in the American League with a record of 77 wins and 85 losses.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-boston-red-sox-season] The **1962 Boston Red Sox season** was the 62nd season in the franchise's Major League Baseball history.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-boston-red-sox-season] The Red Sox finished eighth in the American League (AL) with a record of 76 wins and 84 losses, 19 games behind the AL pennant winner and eventual World Series champion New York Yankees.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The **1962 New York Mets season** was the first regular season for the New York Mets of Major League Baseball (MLB), as the National League returned to New York City for the first time since 1957.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] They went 40–120 (.250) and finished tenth and last in the National League, 60+1⁄2 games behind the NL Champion San Francisco Giants, who had once called New York home.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The Mets were the latest team to be 60+ games behind in a division before the 2018 Baltimore Orioles finished 61 games behind the World Series Champion Boston Red Sox.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] In one of the worst MLB seasons in the modern era and the National League since the 1952 Pittsburgh Pirates, the Mets lost 120 games, setting the record for the most losses in the era.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Their losses became the second most when the 2024 Chicago White Sox lost their 121st game; though their winning percentage (.253) is still higher than the Mets' (.250).
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The Mets' starting pitchers also recorded a new major league low of just 23 wins all season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The team lost its first game 11–4 to the St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Louis Cardinals on April 11 and went on to lose its first nine games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Their first win in franchise history came on April 23 in Pittsburgh in a 9–1 win over the Pittsburgh Pirates, which also resulted in the Pirates' first loss after a 10–0 start.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Their first win in New York came on April 28 in a 9–4 win over the Philadelphia Phillies.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Having repaired their record to 12–19 on May 20 after sweeping a doubleheader against the Milwaukee Braves, the Mets lost their next 17 games.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] They also lost 11 games straight from July 15 to July 26 and 13 games straight from August 9 to August 21.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Their longest winning streak of the season was three wins.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The Mets were managed by former New York Yankees manager Casey Stengel and played their home games at the Polo Grounds, which was their temporary home while Shea Stadium was being built in Queens.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] They remain infamous for their ineptitude and were one of the worst teams in Major League Baseball history.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The team's 120 losses were the third most by any MLB team, after the infamous 1899 Cleveland Spiders lost 134.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Their team batting average, team earned run average (ERA), and team fielding percentage were all the worst in the major leagues that season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Despite the team's terrible performance, fans came out in droves.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Their 1962 season attendance of 922,530 was good enough for sixth in the National League.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The season was chronicled in Jimmy Breslin's humorous best-selling 1963 book *Can't Anybody Here Play This Game?* The title came from a remark made by manager Casey Stengel expressing frustration over his team's poor play.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] One of the only bright spots was left fielder Frank Thomas, who hit .266 with 152 hits, 34 home runs, and 94 RBIs.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The Mets and Houston Colt .45s were established on October 17, 1960, giving them time to acquire minor league professional players, sign amateur free agents (there was no first-year MLB draft until 1965) and enter into working agreements with minor league affiliates during the 1961 season.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] As an expansion team, the Mets were not expected to do well.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] They finished last in the National League, and they also finished 24 games behind their expansion brethren, the Colt .45s.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The first game in franchise history was played on the road, at Busch Stadium, St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Louis, on Wednesday night, April 11, 1962.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] The Mets fell behind 2–0 and 5–2 early, then narrowed the deficit to one run, but ultimately lost to the St.
[src:1962-new-york-mets-season/1962-new-york-mets-season] Former Brooklyn Dodgers Gil Hodges and Charlie Neal homered for the Mets, whose home opener at New York's Polo Grounds would wait until their second-ever official game, on Friday, April 13, 1962.
